sfi.description: roughly oblong mass of indeterminate shape or function; may be more than one element fused together; appears to develop to a point at one end (see second fragment in bag); central element appears oblong in cross-section; heavy corrosion and disintegration; possibly a nail. (3 pieces in bag).

Oblong, rectangular plate, 2 parallel rectilinear sides and one edge perpendicular to them. A 0.8 cm wide section of the length has been folded lengthwise back upon itself (the width above is that of the finished article). At other end a section 1.4 cm deep, has been cut away ca 1.00 cm from the end resulting in a "L" shaped appearance at this terminus. Heavily encrusted, corroded. Green? White (?) corrosion product

(4 parts, 2 major, 2 minor); longitudinal with convergent sides in plan from apparent width 2 cm to 1.5 cm; at 1.5 cm from end, one side obliquely cut to form point with other side; opposite end indistinct; heavily corroded/encrusted.

Rimangono in sito tre filari di blocchi rozzamente sbozzati. Sacco particolarmente accurato nella fattura e con blocchi di grosse dimensioni.

cxt.interpretation: Small feature associated with metal working activity, probably not associated with context 525 or 563
cxt.observations: Possibly related to context 525, probably an extension of context 525 and in between the two has already been removed [Adam doubts this interpretation]. Context [530] did not extend very deep approximately 5 cm. Only 3 datable fragments recovered. Context only recognizable after rainy day.
cxt.description: Dark gray brown ashy soil; 65 X 60 cm N-S/E-W, depth no more than 5 cm; silty with a small gravel; contained industrial debris/metal slag. Filled an irregular cut in surface under last courtyard surface
cxt.definition: Dark ashy soil in NE section of courtyard

cxt.interpretation: Ceramic discussion above needs to be revised: AS's summary table cautiously suggests a date in the 10th or 11th c. (4 fr. GWW II). Consequently, it is possible that the initial interpretation was correct and the feature should be taken in conjunction with the original use of the bedrock cut. Numismatic evidence limited to coin of Leo I (457-474)
cxt.observations: Feature cleaned and removed, by layer, no discrete orientation discerned. Clarification per ATR. Top course looks to preferentially oriented, as such by chance it looks like the course of a wall. Lower layers were not coursed, the feature, was filled with voids, and the stones were not aligned vertically or horisontally, save the top row.
cxt.description: Rough stone construction , possibly and earlier wall in the S. E. corner of room 33. Walling stones in irregular pile leaning against bedrock drop-off in 33, intermixed with bone, cermaics, and plaster fragments.
cxt.definition: Rough stone construction in SE section of room 33 parallel to wall 298

cxt.description: Layer of burning in SW part of room 37. Soft dark soil with ash, small pieces of charcoal. No finds. Irregular limits, seems to fill slight depression in contemporary ground surface, ca. 4cm thick; clearly visible in section
